items.title: PM defends Anika Wells' taxpayer-funded trips to New York, Thredbo
items.standfirst: Prime Minister Anthony Albanese has defended Communications and Sports Minister Anika Wells as her Olympic-sized expenses bills come under scrutiny.
items.content: Prime Minister Anthony Albanese has defended Communications and Sports Minister Anika Wells as her Olympic-sized expenses bills come under scrutiny.Wells' taxpayer-funded travel has copped criticism, with Shadow Industry Minister Alex Hawke saying "whether it's New York, whether it's Paris, whether it's Thredbo, these are expenses that would make the royals blush".Following revelations the communications minister's September trip to the United Nations cost just under $100,000, scrutiny has now turned to her jet-setting as sports minister.READ MORE: Thousands of toys pulled from Victorian stores ahead of ChristmasShe said she was kept very busy in Paris, recalling that "sometimes I was eating a muesli bar in the car".Although not on her first night, dining at a Michelin-star restaurant at a cost of €569 ($1000) for a dinner for four, followed by drinks costing €427 ($750)."We definitely did not go to a second location. From my memory I basically fell asleep at the table and we walked home," Wells told Sky.And when Wells went to Thredbo in support of Paralympians in June, her family tagged along for a ski weekend at taxpayer expense, worth nearly $3000.Wells defended the cost, saying "every parliamentarian has family reunion entitlements".READ MORE: Disaster declared as fire destroys multiple homesThe defence was echoed by Albanese, who told the ABC's Insiders today that "all of the travel was within guidelines"."Anika Wells was working on that [Thredbo] trip as sports minister, participating in the lifting up of parasport. That's been driven by Anika Wells," he told the ABC's Insiders."There are rules there, and I'm not going to go through each and every one. I've got a big job ... It's completely within the rules."There's family reunion entitlements, all the travel that's within the guidelines. She was working and there were announcements and there were events there."While it may be within guidelines, there is scrutiny about whether the expenses meet community standards."If she wants to take her family on a ski holiday, she can pay for it herself," Shadow Finance Minister James Paterson said.DOWNLOAD THE 9NEWS APP: Stay across all the latest in breaking news, sport, politics and the weather via our news app and get notifications sent straight to your smartphone. clusters.neutral_headline: Gang jumps fence, smashes door to steal two BMWs in Logan home invasion

items.title: Gang jumps fence, smashes door to steal two BMWs in Logan home invasion
items.standfirst: Police are hunting for seven people after a gang was caught on CCTV smashing a door and stealing two BMWs in a violent home invasion in Logan.
items.content: Police are hunting for seven people after a gang was caught on CCTV smashing a door and stealing two BMWs in a violent home invasion in Logan, south of Brisbane.The gang jumped the high fence of the Rochedale South home about 1.30am today and and casually cased out the property.Police are also investigating whether the group is behind five other home invasions overnight, with vehicles and other valuables stolen.READ MORE: Disaster declared as fire destroys multiple homes"Everything was locked, gates, alarms, we had cameras, they checked all the doors, all the windows around the bottom, the only way they could get in was to smash through the door," the homeowner said.After grabbing a rock and metal pole, that's exactly what the group did. An alarm scared off one intruder while the others were confronted by one of the homeowners inside."There's so much damage inside, they've thrown rocks through the window to get through, it smashed our stone benchtop, the floor's all scratched from the volume of glass," the victim said.The group grabbed keys and headed for the garage, stealing the family's two BMWs."They hit the pylon of the side of the house when they drove forward, they threw a steel pole at my hubby when he confronted them in the garage," the homeowner said.Both of the vehicles have been found, but the offenders remain on the run.Police say they are hunting at least seven people.Anyone with information can contact Crime Stoppers on 1800 333 000.

items.title: 'Biggest and brightest spark': Tributes for teenager killed in Victoria crash
items.standfirst: A 16-year-old boy alleged to be the driver has been charged.
items.content: A 17-year-old boy is being remembered as "a blessing" after he died in a car accident in Geelong.Emergency services were called to School Road in Corio about 2am today after reports of a crash.Two people – believed to be a driver and a back seat passenger of the car – were treated at the scene by paramedics.READ MORE: Thousands of toys pulled from Victorian stores ahead of ChristmasA third person, a teenager called JJ travelling in the front seat, was also treated by paramedics, however, he died at the scene.His family posted a tribute on social media, remembering him as the world's "biggest and brightest spark"."You were the light in every room and lived life to the absolute fullest," his aunt wrote."Your life was a blessing, your memory will be a treasure, JJ ... you were taken too soon, and had so much more life and love to live and give."READ MORE: Disaster declared as fire destroys multiple homesFriends were seen at the crash site paying tribute to JJ, as police now investigate the cause of the crash. The other people in the car, believed to be JJ's friends, were taken to hospital in a stable condition.They are cooperating with police, who said they are investigating all avenues, including drugs and alcohol.This evening, a 16-year-old boy was charged with culpable driving, dangerous driving cause death and other driving offences.Police have appealed for anyone with any information or footage to contact Crime Stoppers on 1800 333 000.DOWNLOAD THE 9NEWS APP: Stay across all the latest in breaking news, sport, politics and the weather via our news app and get notifications sent straight to your smartphone.
